data-triple-N3.o: "The parsec is a unit of length used in astronomy, equal to about 30.9 trillion kilometres. In astronomical terms, it is equal to 3.26 light-years, and in scientific terms it is equal to 3.09×10 kilometres (1.92×10 miles). The name parsec is "an abbreviated form of 'a distance corresponding to a parallax of one arc second'. " It was coined in 1913 at the suggestion of British astronomer Herbert Hall Turner."@en
